crops.description: From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (29 packages.) "Bronka;" early variety. According to Mr. H. C. Warner, of the State Board of Agriculture of South Dakota, this variety produced heads a little earlier than the Jersey Wakefield, but they were too small for market.
From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1808. (62 packages.) "Genuine white Bulgarian."

From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1858. (7 packages.) A white variety from Ladoga Lake region. Mr. Warner also experimented with this number and found it of medium quality, Imat with the type not well fixed and the heads mostly louse. He states that it is not to be compared for value with Succession, Vandergaw, or Flat Dutch.
From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (5 packages.) " White Reval."
From Moscow, Russia, Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1858 (61 packages.) " Genuine white Saburovka, fine for sauerkraut."
From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (40 packages.) " Earliest white."

crops.origin: Moscow, Russia; Kiakuta, Siberia, on border of Mongolia
crops.description: From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. "Prof. Rytow ;" said to be a peculiar dwarf variety for culture in dwellings. From Kiakuta, Siberia, on border of Mongolia. (30 packages.)
From Moscow, Russia, Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (260 packages.) " Aksel Dwarf." Very early; originated in the Province of Perm.
From Moscow, Russin. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (58 packages.) "Galachov Dwarf."

From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (823 packages.) " Krasnoselki cabbage turnip." Mr. H. Benton, of the Experiment Station at Uniontown, Ala., reports: " Quantity equal to any other variety ; quality best of fourteen varieties grown on the station farm this season." A Kansas correspondent, on the other hand, says that the quality is poor, tough, and woody.
From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. " Genuine Petrovski table."*
From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (64 packages.) " Rostov Sugar." Best Russian variety for drying.

From Moscow, Russia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, February, 1898. (6 packages.) Earliest sweet corn from Malachows. Reported from Alabama as "worthless in this locality." Report from Kansas: "Yield good, quality fine, variety very early."
